Attended a beautiful day to celebrate love! We had so much fun attending the Haldi ceremony for the extended family. The whole event was filled with so much joy and laughter, and we loved getting to see everyone dressed in their traditional yellow clothing.

Haldi is a traditional Indian ceremony that is held before the wedding day. It is a time for the bride and groom to be cleansed and purified, and to receive the blessings of their family and friends. The turmeric paste that is used in the ceremony is said to have many benefits, including promoting good skin health, warding off evil spirits, and bringing good luck.

I used to struggle with slicing artisan bread. My slices were always either too thick or uneven. After a few trials and errors, I finally found a way to cut the bread perfectly, even with thin slices.
Here’s how I do it:
	0.	Score the bread on each side with a sharp knife. This helps to prevent the bread from tearing.
	0.	Bring the knife in the center and cut through the middle, joining both the edges.
	0.	Voila! You have a perfect slice of artisan bread.
Here are some additional tips:
	•	Use a sharp knife. A dull knife will make it difficult to get a clean cut.
	•	Cut the bread in half first, then slice it into individual slices. This will help to keep the slices from being too thick.

These refreshing and healthy popsicles are perfect for a hot summer day! Made with pink lemon zest and juice, dried lychee, mint, watermelon, and strawberries, they’re naturally sweet and free of added sugar. Simply blend all the ingredients together, pour into molds, and freeze until solid. Enjoy!

Ingredients:

1 pink lemon, zested and juiced
1 cup dried lychee
2 cups watermelon, chopped
1 cup strawberries, hulled and sliced
1/2 cup sugar-free sweetener
Instructions:

Combine all the ingredients in a blender and blend until smooth.
Pour the mixture into popsicle molds and freeze until solid.
Enjoy!

This waffle is an eye candy but instead of running away from it, I ate it (Not all, keep reading if you want to know why???). Somehow diets have never worked for me whether I am trying to lose or maintain weight.

Over the years I realized that diet won’t ever work for me. We are a household of foodies and that will never stop. Dieting meant depriving my family of Good Delicious Food. Since I am in charge of cooking, I needed to change my mindset about eating rather than excluding foods from my diet. 

Here is what has worked for me:

	⁃	I can't control what others eat just because I'm on a diet. There will always be temptations, and it's not fair to make myself miserable or cause discomfort to those around me. So, I've learned to indulge but keep an eye on portion sizes, even sharing that chocolate cake slice I could devour in one bite.
	⁃	I expanded my palate to appreciate food swaps such as using half rice and half cauliflower rice, incorporating mushrooms, or opting for low-carb noodles, among others. It wasn't easy initially, but over time, I adapted.
	⁃	I started adding more raw vegetables. Starting the meal with carrots, cucumbers or a bowl of raw veggies helps me with portion control.
	⁃	The most cliché advice, but the hardest to follow, is being mindful. Even if I overindulged in one meal, I've learned to reflect and make adjustments in my next one. I ask myself if I can reduce the calories, incorporate more veggies, drink more water, and focus on protein and fiber. Some may raise their eyebrows, but I've even skipped a meal to give my body a break.
	⁃	And let's not forget the importance of exercise- our body is our lifeline. This enables our bodies to stand strong even in the face of bad choices we make.

It's been quite a journey, but I've realized that changing my mindset about eating is the key to maintaining a healthy and happy relationship with food. 🍽️💪 So next time that waffle shows up I am not running away from it!

With Diwali around the corner here I am starting a Diwali Special Series so we can eat better. 

This is Indian version of a dinner plate called a thali is seriously underrated. Since Indian meals have so much variety, this plate is super useful so curries don’t flow into each other and you can enjoy them separately. I love it because it can partition my food and help me see if I am hitting different food groups. I can then add more protein or veggies to my meal.

I served myself daal (protein and carbs), aloo methi (carbs), green chutney, roti (carbs), and chicken (protein), adding more veggies to it. This helps me adjust my food and gives me a bird’s-eye view of what I am eating and how much. Otherwise, everything gets mixed up, and you end up eating a lot more than you thought you were. CHEESECAKE FILLING:8 oz light cream cheese softened to room temperature
2 large eggs
1/3 -1/2 cup sugar substitute
1 cup nonfat plain Greek yogurt
1 teaspoon vanilla extract

CHEESECAKE BASE
1/2 cup blueberries for base crust

BLUEBERRY TOPPING FOR CHEESECAKE:
3/4 cup of blueberries for the top layer
1/2 cup water
1 1/2 tsp of cornstarch

Preheat oven to 320°F.
 Blend all the filling ingredients in a blender
Take an oven-resistant pan ( I used a 5x5 ) glass Tupperware bottom
Added my 1/2 cup of blueberries as a base
Bake it in the oven for 30 mins. (Please monitor your time as depending on the pan you bake in this can vary)
In the meantime, heat the topping blueberries in a saucepan, and add 1/2 cup of water. 
Let it cook and soften. 
Now add the cornstarch. Once the mixture is thickened, stop
Let the topping cool a bit and then add to the top of cheesecake.
